text.tspan: Where a client appoints contractors, the roles and responsibilities of all parties are to be agreed and defined. This should bedocumented using the form “OO 3 – Minutes of Kick of Meeting”. The procedures in Section 12.2.3 above shall also be complied with.12.3MONITORING, ASSESSMENT AND FEEDBACK12.3.1DAILY MEETING BETWEEN CONTRACTORS AND SHIP’S STAFFA daily meeting is to be carried out onboard between Contractor and ship’s personnel and documented using the form “OP 13 –Minutes of Daily Meeting with Contractors”.12.3.2REPORTING OF ACCIDENTS / INCIDENTS / NEAR MISSESThe contractor shall report all Accidents / Incidents / Near Misses promptly to the Master who shall in turn follow the procedures laiddown in “HSEQA Manual 15.2.5 - ACCIDENTS, INCIDENTS, NEAR-MISSES, UNSAFE ACTS, UNSAFE CONDITIONS AND NONCONFORMITIES”.12.3.3MONTHLY REPORT FROM THE CONTRACTOR, REVIEW AND ASSESSMENTThe contractor shall provide a Monthly report using the form “OO 4 – Contractors Monthly Report” which shall be sent at the end tohead office for review/ assessment by HSEQA and Technical and Operations departments as appropriate. Any issues of concern thatare noted shall be communicated to the contractor for necessary action and follow up.12.3.4PERFORMANCE FEEDBACKThe company shall provide feedback to the contractor on his performance every 3 months or at the end of the contract (if less than 3months) using the form “OO 5 – Contractor Performance Feedback”.12.3.5ANNUAL ASSESSMENTAn Assessment is to be carried out annually of all Contractors who are in the Company’s Approved list of Contractors to determine ifthe Contractor remains “Approved” is on “Caution” or has been changed to “Not approved”. The “Approved list” shall be updatedaccordingly.13ANNEX13.1ANNEX 1 INSTRUCTIONS TO OBSERVERS1) Prior takeover of any second-hand vessel, we place on board observers (usually senior officers) who are required to make a studyof the vessel’s conditions and the same involves 3 major functions:a) As observers to be a witness if some untoward incident takes place before delivery of the vesselb) To make a list of spares, stores and repairs that may be needed urgently on takeover of the vesselc) To familiarize with the running and maintenance of the ships equipment and systems which will assist our staff as the Seller’s crewdeparts.2) As you are joining the vessel you may be asked by the seller to sign a letter of indemnity which essentially indemnifies the presentowner against a claim for personal injury. It will be in order to sign such an indemnity as our company maintains a cover for you.3) Upon joining the vessel please send a message to office confirming your joining the vessel. Please also give vessel’s voyageitinerary with agent’s full style and address for each port, if possible. We would also like to know vessel’s email address and othercontact details. You can discuss this with the Master and if he insists for any communication charges, this can be settled at the time ofdelivery.4) We would like to have the ship’s position report once a week, say every Monday, giving position, speed, RPM and ETA next port.5) As you will appreciate, ship’s staff may be generally suspicious of your presence. Your first task is to win their confidence so thatthey can talk to you freely on technical matters as a shipmate. You can achieve the above by giving a helping hand to the existingship’s staff. For our part, our main object is to establish a factual position and working of all equipment as they are on board and beguided by the Memorandum of Agreement.6) There are two of the standard clauses in the ship sale / purchase contract, which are relevant to the observer and are as follows:a) Spares / bunkers etc:
